        # API_CHANGES.txt | text | 413w
        P[38]:
          .. -*- rest -*- | 4w
          ==================================================
        API chang | 10w
          Masked arrays are subclasses of ndarray
        -------------------- | 7w
          Contrary to the original implementation, masked arrays are n | 11w
          >>> x = masked_array([1,2,3],mask=[0,0,1])
          >>> print isins | 9w
          ``_data`` returns a view of the masked array
        --------------- | 9w
          Masked arrays are composed of a ``_data`` part and a ``_mask | 30w
          >>> x = masked_array(numpy.matrix([[1,2],[3,4]]),mask=[[0,0] | 16w
          In practice, ``_data`` is implemented as a property, not as  | 29w
          >>>x._data is x._data
          False | 4w
          ``filled(x)`` can return a subclass of ndarray
        ------------- | 20w
          >>> x = masked_array(numpy.matrix([[1,2],[3,4]]),mask=[[0,0] | 22w
          ``put``, ``putmask`` behave like their ndarray counterparts
         | 8w
          Previously, ``putmask`` was used like this:: | 6w
          mask = [False,True,True]
          x = array([1,4,7],mask=mask)
          pu | 7w
          which translated to:: | 3w
          x[~mask] = [3] | 3w
          (Note that a ``True``-value in a mask suppresses a value.) | 10w
          In other words, the mask had the same length as ``x``, where | 16w
          Now, the behaviour is similar to that of ``ndarray.putmask`` | 23w
          :: | 1w
          putmask(x,mask,[3,0,0]) | 1w
          ``fill_value`` is a property
        ---------------------------- | 5w
          ``fill_value`` is no longer a method, but a property:: | 9w
          >>> print x.fill_value
          999999 | 4w
          ``cumsum`` and ``cumprod`` ignore missing values
        ----------- | 7w
          Missing values are assumed to be the identity element, i.e.  | 17w
          >>> x = N.ma.array([1,2,3,4],mask=[False,True,False,False])
         | 25w
          ``bool(x)`` raises a ValueError
        ---------------------------- | 5w
          Masked arrays now behave like regular ``ndarrays``, in that  | 15w
          :: | 1w
          >>> x = N.ma.array([1,2,3])
          >>> bool(x)
          Traceback (most  | 35w
          ==================================
        New features (non exhaust | 7w
          ``mr_``
        ------- | 2w
          ``mr_`` mimics the behavior of ``r_`` for masked arrays:: | 9w
          >>> np.ma.mr_[3,4,5]
          masked_array(data = [3 4 5],
                 | 11w
          ``anom``
